##### **§1. Phenomenon Overview**

Our chosen phenomenon focuses on the fabrication of echo chambers during disasters on centralized social media platforms, created and facilitated by bot interactions. Specifically, we’re investigating the presence of these interactions on X and similar social networking, microblogging, and news platforms. We highlight how bots will tend to manipulate users seeking information by spreading disinformation, leading users to believe the content they see is accurate. Hajli et al. (2022) speak about the formation of these echo chambers and opinion manipulation, stating “social bots spread a given on-line opinion over social media platforms, leading to the misconception that other humans share the ‘bot opinion’” (p. 1246). Resultantly, bots will collaborate or compete against one another to have their opinions be shared with the largest human audience. Through bots using techniques to prevent being detected and removed, such as interacting with one another to auto-sort, disinformation AI bots ultimately also interact with the AI recommendation algorithms on X. These bots will deceive the algorithms by using numerous techniques that make the platform’s algorithms believe that their content is popular, thus having their messages be spread further. Tahora Hossein Nazer (2019) states that one of these techniques is that “These bots latch trending hashtags to their messages to push them higher in the social media search results” (p. 12). During disasters, these hashtags tend to relate to the present disaster event and will draw many more eyes to them than most other hashtags. As a result, posts containing misinformation made by the bots are spread throughout the media ecosystem to consumers by recommendation algorithms. This creates a snowball effect, as more users engage with the posts and drive analytics for the recommendation algorithms to push the bot-driven disinformation more alongside new posts made by causally misinformed humans. 

During critical times of disasters, platforms such as X are becoming saturated with bots that are mainly spreading disinformation. This manipulates human emotions and jeopardizes public safety for those seeking reliable updates and news, undermining trust in information and eroding public confidence. The impacts of these bots spreading disinformation during disasters also go beyond the time of disasters, as echo chambers created during this time remain on the platforms. This is often due to the disinformation regarding political agendas, influencing public perception of disaster responses to support or discredit governments and organizations. Ultimately, this leads to user radicalization, as they perceive bots as legitimate sources, further deepening polarization and division. Cheng et al. (2022) describe this as “inferior opinions are silenced and the superior opinions are expressed and accessible to others; the dominant opinions expand and strengthen in a spiral manner, and eventually manipulate public opinion” (p. 2), describing bot interactions as being the superior. Resultingly, this creates an uncomfortable environment for those with opposing viewpoints and an erosion of critical thinking, leading to users leaving the platform.

Agent-based modelling offers a reliable approach to investigating the impact of these bots. While not entirely accurate, it allows us to model the effects of malicious bots and learn how to prevent their influence. Using agent-based modelling, we can conduct our research and testing without needing a disaster to occur in real-time, allowing us to be proactive in preventative measures of these bots before disinformation spreads. Agent-based modelling also enables us to conduct foundational investigations and tests consistently and efficiently, without interference from real-world variables. Through these initial studies on the simulations, researchers can take these findings to apply additional real-world factors to study the platform more deeply.

##### **§2. Simulation Design & Implementation**

The simulation we have created is based on the Schelling Segregation Model. Unlike the original Schelling Segregation Model, where each agent only has a single type, our model reflects each agent as having two types. The first type is the class type, indicating whether they are a human or a bot agent. The second type is the knowledge type, indicating disinformational or informational. In the context of our two types of agents, each has different implications. For human agents, the knowledge type demonstrates whether they are informed or disinformed, where a green circle indicates an informed human, and an orange circle indicates a disinformed human. For bot agents, the knowledge type refers to the kind of information they generate. Both informational and disinformational bots display as grey squares to reflect the real-world difficulty in identifying bots or verifying information produced. Additionally, similar to the real world, the disinformational bots in our simulation greatly outnumber the informational bots. A key component of the simulation is also the disaster system, which is the only time bots appear on the grid. This differs from the Schelling model, which operates with consistent parameters throughout its simulations. In contrast, our simulation has a normal operation, where only the human agents are present, and a disaster operation prompted by a corresponding dialog, where bots appear and coexist with humans on the platform. During normal operation, human agents can influence each other and alter their knowledge type based on their own. During the disaster operation, bot agents can influence human agents to change their knowledge type based on the bots' knowledge type. In both operations, human agents move based on their homophily of being surrounded by agents sharing the same knowledge type, causing echo chambers to emerge. The echo chambers create large groupings of disinformation and information surrounding the current disaster, segregating humans based on their knowledge influenced primarily by bots.

	The agents exist on a two-dimensional grid representing X, where each agent moves and interacts around the grid, representing users exploring various content created by other users throughout X. The grid allows us to easily display our agents moving around the platform and show grouping of agents into echo chambers in a visually understandable way. However, the two-dimensional grid represents a simplified way that content is distributed to convey information and disinformation from one user to another. Typically,  information and disinformation are not translated solely through encountering a user's content and often include further exploration. For example, within X, there are numerous ways to navigate through the feeds of content due to hyperlinks, such as clicking on profiles, hashtags, and more. Navigating the application reveals that users encounter different levels of dimensions on the platform where information and disinformation can spread. However, the grid-based simulation environment can only convey one of these levels, showing that agent interaction of spreading information or disinformation occurs on the surface as a simple interaction of encountering a single piece of content. 

Agents interact with neighboring agents within a one-space radius, equivalent to a chess king’s move. During a normal operation, humans have a 15% chance of changing their neighbouring agent of opposite knowledge type to be the same as themself. During a disaster operation, bots enter the simulation and have a percentage based on the model slider of changing their neighbouring human agent of opposite knowledge type to be the same as themself. Instead of using a deterministic system where every knowledge transition is predefined, using probability allowed for a more simplified approach. By assigning probabilities to knowledge type changes, we avoided the need for a complex set of rules that manually dictated every possible transition. This aided us in modelling uncertainty that aligned with real-world behaviour. Additionally, our agents move throughout the grid based on different factors. Human agents will move based on their neighbours and a homophily determined by a percentage based on a model slider. If the proportion of a human agent’s neighbours that share its belief is less than the homophily, then the human agent will move to a different spot. Our bot agents will move if one of their neighbouring agents shares the same knowledge type and if there is an available spot that is not next to another bot. This simplified movement of the bots allows our simulation to be more dynamic, preventing stagnation and bottlenecks. It displays realistic social influence where a single like-minded connection can be enough to reinforce beliefs and trigger movement.

The simulation uses RandomActivation for the scheduler. RandomActivation prevents execution bias, as agents are activated in a random order every step, where no agent consistently acts first. This resembles real-world interactions where interactions do not occur in a strict order, closely modelling the unpredictability of human and bot interactions. Our scheduler has the disaster operation occur at a random step, simulating the unpredictability of disasters striking the real world. After several steps, the simulation returns to normal operation but cycles through the steps again. This represents the natural state of our world, where disasters occur periodically and shows how the platform can never be in a neutral state due to bots that occur when these disasters happen. Resultantly, bot-to-bot interactions primarily emerge and evolve during disaster operations, and humans carry on these effects during normal operations. When bots appear during the disaster operation, they will move throughout the grid but avoid moving next to one another to simulate agent coordination, autosorting, and avoidance of detection by the algorithm. This bot-to-bot interaction occurs throughout the simulation, displaying how algorithms are challenged with being able to detect bots and remove them. Additionally, a key assumption is that information and disinformation are spread by the recommendation algorithms on the platform throughout the simulation, influencing human users even outside of the disaster operations. This demonstrates an additional bot-to-bot interaction as the recommendation algorithms aid the bots in spreading their content. 

The simulation collected several types of data to track how disinformation spreads and persists within a network. First, it recorded the states of individual agents, whether they were informed or disinformed at each step or cycle. This provided a means to track the progression of the total disinformed and informed humans over time, visually reflected through line graphs. The simulation also captured the timing of external events such as disasters and bot activity. By correlating these events with changes in disinformation levels, we could identify crisis periods where bot activity led to spikes in misinformation and how these effects persisted even after bots became inactive. The simulation collected other data such as the cumulative homophily of agents and the number of clusters. This data showed us when agents were most happy and when they were not, overall impacting their movement across the grid and leading to the formation of echo chambers. However, implementing these data collection and visualization components posed several challenges. One key issue was ensuring that bots did not spawn nearby or move constantly. This restriction was vital to capturing the interactions between bots and human agents, enabling a more precise evaluation of bot-driven influences on human behavior. Additionally, we faced difficulties depicting the link between disasters and the emergence of echo chambers. We had to establish each agent's baseline behavior before a disaster and then determine how they would react to both the crisis and each other during and after the event. This process involved setting baseline behaviors for human agents and meticulously modeling the changes in these behaviors in response to disasters.


##### **§3. Observations & Results**

The simulation displays how bots, during a time of disaster when users are most vulnerable, will take advantage of humans and spread disinformation by flocking to platforms. A human may be more susceptible to being influenced or tricked by bots, particularly when preoccupied with other significant concerns regarding the disaster. In such circumstances, the individual’s cognitive resources and attention are stretched thin, making them less likely to assess critically or question the information presented. This vulnerability allows bots to exploit emotional distress or uncertainty, leading to the spread of disinformation. The combination of external stressors and a diminished ability to focus on new information can result in the individual accepting misleading or false content, further deepening their disinformation. This influence of users on the platform leads to the creation of echo chambers and radicalization. 

![][image6]

The graph above shows the total humans informed and illustrates how bots contributed to the formation of disinformed human agents, ultimately leading to the creation of echo chambers. The X-axis of the chart shows the number of steps, while the Y-axis displays the number of human agents. The beginning steps displayed in the graph show an increase in informed humans during the normal operation due to bots not being present on the platform yet. During this operation, there is a majority of informed humans who are influencing their neighbours around them. However, once the disaster occurs, we can see that bots can affect over a third of the human agents before their influence slows due to the formation of echo chambers. During this operation, human agents begin to move based on their homophily to surround themselves with like-minded knowledge types, making them less accessible for bots and human agents of the opposite type to disinform. Additionally, informational bots present an attempt to spread information but fail to fully succeed due to being outnumbered by disinformation bots. Around step 40, we can see another increase in informed humans due to the disaster ending and bots disappearing from the platform. This is a result of human users attempting to neutralize the platform, however, we can see that it is unsuccessful in having the number of total humans informed be at the same peak as before the disaster occurred. The decline in informed humans is further driven by disinformed human agents spreading disinformation during normal operations, with their influence being increasingly stronger in numbers as the platform becomes more saturated with disinformed users. The cycle then repeats, loosely resembling an exponential decay. The effectiveness of real-world disinformation bots is often limited by certain barriers, such as people being more cautious or critical of information under normal circumstances. However, during disasters, these barriers are weakened or removed. People are more vulnerable due to heightened stress, uncertainty, and urgency. This creates an environment where disinformation bots can more easily spread false or misleading information. The comparison to the simulation suggests that, at the start of the simulation, conditions are ripe for disinformation to flourish, much like during a disaster in real life, where people are more susceptible to manipulation.

![][image7]

	In the simulation grid above on the left, each circle represents a human agent in the simulation, where green indicates informed humans and orange denotes those who have become disinformed. The bots are no longer on the grid and have become inactive due to the simulation moving beyond the disaster operation. However, a significant number of humans remain disinformed, highlighting how disinformation can linger long after its initial source of content disappears. In real-world scenarios, the same pattern can occur. Despite bots or other sources of misinformation becoming inactive, the misinformation introduced by these agents can continue to spread among people who have already absorbed and shared it. This shows how crucial it is to address and detect disinformation early and consistently, as removing or deactivating the source once the spread has occurred does not suffice in preventing its impact from persisting on the social media platform. This is evident in the graph above on the right, showcasing the total humans disinformed. The X-axis represents the number of human agents, and the Y-axis represents the number of steps. Upon analysis, it is evident that the total humans disinformed does not drop close to its initial numbers closer to the beginning of the simulation and instead increases.

![][image8]

The graph above displays the number of clusters of like-minded human agents throughout the simulation, formed when human agents are happy with the neighbours around them. The Y-axis represents the number of clusters, and the X-axis represents the number of steps. As agents become satisfied with their surroundings, they stop moving and become stationed on that spot on the grid. Over time, as more agents reach this state of satisfaction, movement decreases, leading to the formation of echo chambers where agents with similar knowledge types cluster together. These clusters are driven by the influence of disinformation and information from bots, curating a situation where an increasing number of human agents are avoiding those with opposite knowledge types. Notably, the platform becomes saturated with disinformational human clusters due to the disinformational bots outnumbering informational bots and heavily influencing the majority of humans on the grid. Resultantly, it becomes challenging for informational bots to disrupt these clusters, and the cumulative number of clusters continues to increase over time.

![][image9]

	An unexpected behaviour and emergent dynamic occurred when analyzing the graph above, representing the total number of happy agents. The Y-axis represents the number of human agents, and the X-axis represents the number of steps. At the beginning of the simulation, before step 20 and during the normal operation, human agents become steadily happy but begin displaying some signs of unhappiness through some dips and peaks as shown on the graph. This could be due to the majority of the human agents on the simulation being initiated as informed human agents, thus, most agents begin happy as the probability of an informed human being neighboured by another informed human is high. However, as the few disinformed bots move around the grid searching for one another, this movement may cause slight decreases in overall happiness. Additionally, during this operation, human agents have a small chance of influencing one another, which could contribute to the minimal dips. Past step 20 and during the disaster operation, we see a drastic drop in happiness as bots appear on the grid and convert the knowledge types of numerous human agents. The sporadic movement of bots creates the dips as they attempt to change numerous humans with opposite knowledge types. In contrast to human agents influencing one another during normal operation, bots have a greater chance of changing their human agent's knowledge type and moving more often. This allows them to impact more human agents, resulting in deeper dips than during normal operation. The steps that followed the disaster operation were unexpected, as the human agents were able to regain their homophily. We suspect that the reason may be similar to why homophily was high at the start of the simulation, but with most human agents now being disinformed instead. Correspondingly, the probability of a disinformed human agent being neighboured by another disinformed agent is high. However, this does not occur long before another disaster operation occurs, and the pattern reappears again.

##### **§4. Ethical & Societal Reflections**

Apart from the sources referenced for inspiration, our simulation is not directly based on real-world data. As a result, ethical considerations are taken into account when applying insights from our simulation to real-world social media platforms.

	In our simulation, we are only aware of the bot agents due to them being a different colour and shape from the rest. However, we make the key assumption that the human agents in our simulation are vulnerable to bot agents because they are indistinguishable from other human agents. Correspondingly, on a real-world platform, the challenge remains to distinguish a bot account from a human account. With a high volume of content distributed throughout platforms during disaster scenarios, a large amount of data would need to be analyzed to identify disinformation bots. This implies human users being impacted by privacy issues, as every user's data would need to be scoped to determine whether an account is a bot and to prevent a human user from being falsely identified as a bot. This also brings the possibility of human data usage to train detection algorithms in identifying human behaviour in comparison to bot behaviour.

	Moreover, integrated into our simulation is the assumption of a human agent being disinformed or informed based on a single interaction with a bot. In a real-world platform, coming to this conclusion would imply additional privacy issues where the surveillance of a human user's interactions on a platform would have to be closely monitored to determine whether they are informed or disinformed. Additionally, unlike in our simulation where echo chambers are visibly clear, this is less apparent on real-world platforms. To identify whether human users are present in echo chambers, additional data would need to be analyzed to determine the type of content that appears on their recommended feeds. In both scenarios, this includes data such as the posts they engage with, the accounts they visit, and the keywords they search for.

The findings in our simulation concern elements of micro, meso, and macro issues in human-to-bot interactions. Despite the simulation environment considering a single social media platform with a very limited number of humans and bots, we can still see how bots influence the platform and manipulate the narrative over time. At the micro level, bots manipulate the platform's algorithm to ensure human users directly interact with and perceive their content. From there, human users interpret the content presented by the bots, using their cognition to process, store, and apply the disinformation or information. This can result in human users being influenced and gaining a social connection to the bot, despite them being unknowingly exposed to disinformation. This social connection builds trust and credibility in the bot's content and posts, fostering symbolic interactionism through shared understandings. The disinformation spread by bots is also in conjunction with human users who engage in discussions on the platform that create groups aligning with the meso level. As these groups form echo chambers and bots reinforce users' beliefs, the platform becomes increasingly segregated and radicalized. This makes constructive dialogue, critical thinking, and mutual understanding more difficult for users, as constant reinforcement of existing beliefs reduces users' ability to think critically and evaluate information objectively. These impacts extend beyond a single platform, as the disinformation or information spread by bots can impact how a large number of users perceive the real world. At a macro level, humans are capable of spreading disinformation and information received from bots outside of the platform, having their content reach into society. Bots spreading content that shapes political agendas can influence public perception of disaster responses, either supporting or discrediting governments and organizations, ultimately affecting power structures. This highlights bots' ability to influence society beyond the platform where they originated.

The patterns of echo chambers have been studied and are evident across numerous platforms through recommendation algorithms. Using the Schelling segregation model allows us to model real-world patterns of threshold-based decision and self-reinforcing segregation. In our model, agents relocate if they are unhappy with their surroundings, reflecting users engaging with content that aligns with their existing beliefs or ignoring opposing views, reinforcing ideological clusters. Additionally, in our model, once clusters emerge, agents have little incentive to move back into mixed areas, which emulates echo chambers forming on platforms and the difficulty for diversity to break in. However, the model has several limitations that differentiate it from the real world. The Schelling-based grid system limits the complexity and number of interactions that can be performed. This simplicity allows us to demonstrate more distinct echo chambers of informed and disinformed users, however, it creates stricter boundaries based on rule-based behaviours in contrast to real-world platforms. On real-world platforms, there’s a greater variety of opinions from a diverse range of people who will believe different kinds of disinformation and information presented to them, where a user may be along a scale of not being entirely informed or disinformed. Additionally, we are also unable to understand the workings of a black boxed recommendation algorithm similar to the one present on the platform X, making it more difficult to propose that the model is emblematic of the platform.

In theory, this simulation could be used by malicious actors who create disinformation bots to discover and test the most effective ways to spread disinformation across different social media platforms. While the simulation is simplified and does not account for direct user interactions, it could still provide insights into how bots might influence a system by interacting with other agents, leading to the formation of clusters. By adjusting the parameters, malicious actors could explore different strategies for bot placement and behaviour, gaining a better understanding of how to influence large-scale online dynamics and potentially spread disinformation more effectively.

##### **§5. Lessons Learned & Future Directions**

Creating our initial simulation design was a fairly smooth process, as we all had a consistent conceptualization of how we wanted the simulation to appear and perform. Our prior coding experience also allowed us to map out how the logic of our interactions would unfold and emerge throughout the simulation. However, upon implementation, the development proved to be a challenging process. Arguably, the biggest challenge our team faced was working with the foundational Mesa Schelling model code while being unfamiliar with the Python environment and development practices. As a result, we faced challenges such as understanding dependencies, command-line operations, and the overall code structure. We were unfamiliar with many of Python's library functions, which we had to rely on to have our agents interact as we wanted. To combat these challenges, we dedicated a significant amount of time to developing and refining our prototype, learning and improving as we encountered errors and bugs. Additionally, we scaled back our simulation design to simplify the interactions and focus on key dynamics.

An early design challenge that had to be scaled back on was how complex we could make agent behaviours given our knowledge and the timeframe. The initial design was to implement a spectrum of values for agent knowledge type, to represent varying degrees of extremism or moderation. For our human agents, this would imply how strongly they feel regarding certain topics on social media platforms. After learning the scope of what we could create, this idea was reduced to specific values to represent particular points or thresholds in knowledge rather than a spectrum. This overly simplifies how the simulation represents real-life environments, as in reality, people's opinions differentiate based on the information they believe, their ideologies, and values. Similarly, our method for users becoming radicalized in the simulation is highly oversimplified compared to real-world dynamics. On a real-world platform, users interact with bot content on varying degrees. Some may not think twice about a bot post and hold their beliefs, some may only agree with it minimally, and some could have their whole belief changed based on it. Resultantly, the formation of echo chambers would be more progressive and gradual. Due to our simulation not implementing this scale of knowledge, the formation of echo chambers is unrealistic and happens suddenly. A future refinement could include adding more values to represent more points and thresholds, and progressing to create a scale as we initially wanted.

After narrowing our scope and continuing development, we encountered issues with the creation of our disaster system, particularly regarding how it connects and can be applied to the real world. In our simulation, bots only exist on the platform during disasters. However, in reality, it is unrealistic to expect bots not to have a presence on a platform before a disaster occurs, and it’s especially unrealistic to expect bots to disappear from a platform when a disaster is over. Although bots are more active during a disaster and will take advantage of the situation,  it’s illogical for it to be their only time of reaching users. However, to implement disasters into our simulation and differentiate it from normal disinformation echo chambers, this was the only solution which we could devise and implement given the timeframe. 

Despite these issues, our findings can be applied to real-world platforms in the future. Our findings show how the long-term implications of echo chambers and disinformation on platforms completely transform the media ecosystem for users. X and platforms like it need to be held accountable for regulating disinformation on their platforms and ensure effective measures are in place to limit bot-generated content and interactions from reaching human users. By refining their bot detection algorithms and implementing fact-checking measures, platforms like X can create a safer and more reliable environment for users, especially during disasters and critical moments.
